-- Structural Rules (Exchange, Weakening, Contraction)
--
-- Classical: Free structural rules (exchange, weakening, contraction)
-- CredTT: CONDITIONAL structural rules
--         Exchange: unconditional
--         Weakening: only if added assumption @ 1 or neutral
--         Contraction: only with explicit duplication permission
--
-- These are NOT free in CredTT!

-- EXCHANGE: Reorder assumptions
-- Gamma, A, B, Delta |- C  implies  Gamma, B, A, Delta |- C
-- This is FREE in CredTT (order doesn't affect credence)

postulate a : A @ c1
postulate b : B @ c2

-- Order A, B or B, A doesn't matter
-- Credence is the same either way

-- WEAKENING: Add unused assumption
-- Gamma |- C @ c  implies  Gamma, A |- C @ c
-- This is CONDITIONAL in CredTT!

-- If A @ 1 (neutral): weakening is safe
postulate neutral : A @ 1
-- Adding A @ 1 to context doesn't change other credences

-- If A @ c < 1: weakening may not be safe
-- Adding uncertain assumption can affect reasoning
postulate uncertain : A @ 1/2
-- Careful: this might interact with other credences

-- CONTRACTION: Use assumption multiple times
-- Gamma, A, A |- C  implies  Gamma, A |- C
-- This requires EXPLICIT PERMISSION in CredTT!

-- Why? Because using A twice is:
-- First use: A @ c
-- Second use: A @ c (but do we "consume" credence?)

-- In linear/affine settings, contraction is restricted
-- CredTT can track this via credence consumption

postulate duplicable : A @ 1
-- Using duplicable @ 1 multiple times is fine

postulate non_duplicable : Resource @ c
-- Using this twice might require c^2, not c

-- The KEY insight:
-- Classical logic has free structural rules
-- This hides important resource/credence tracking
-- CredTT makes these costs EXPLICIT

-- Practical consequence:
-- Proofs that silently reuse assumptions
-- are being DISHONEST about credence cost
-- CredTT forces you to account for reuse
